sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]},{"name":"Robinson","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Robin  , a pet form of   Robert  , + <i>-son</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","French: from a pet form of the personal name   Robin  .","West Indian (including Haiti) and Guyanese: most likely not (only) of English or French origin as in 1 above and 2 above, but also, if not mostly, from the related name of the famous Daniel Defoe's literary character <i>Robinson Crusoe</i> (from a novel first published in 1719)."]},{"name":"Robert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Gilles, Normand, Armand, Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Michel, Edouard, Gaston, Yves.","French, Walloon, English, German, Dutch, Flemish, and Breton (of French origin); Hungarian (<b>Róbert</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ro(d)bert</i> (Middle English <i>Robert</i>, Old French <i>Ro(d)bert</i>), composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This is found occasionally in Anglo-Saxon England before the Conquest, but in the main it was introduced into England by the Normans and quickly became popular among all classes of society. Pet forms and diminutives are found from an early date,   Robin   being particularly common. Compare   Robair  ,   Robar  ,   Robare  , and   Rober  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Robbin","meanings":["English: variant of   Robin  ."]},{"name":"Robinet","meanings":["French: from a pet form of the personal name   Robin  ."]},{"name":"Robbins","meanings":["English: variant of   Robin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Robyn","meanings":["Variant of   Robin  ."]},{"name":"Robins","meanings":["English: from the personal name   Robin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Maredudd ap Robin was born about 1090, in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the son of Robin ap Gruffudd. He had at least 1 son with Gwenhwyfar ferch Madog."},"et":{"about 1090–":"umbes 1090–Surnud","1090–Male":"1090–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1115–1145":"1115–1145","–Male":"Surnud","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","about 1090":"umbes 1090","1145":"1145","about 1115":"umbes 1115","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales","of Cynllaith,Swydd y Waun,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1090–":"noin 1090–Kuollut","1090–Male":"1090–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1115–1145":"1115–1145","–Male":"Kuollut","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","about 1090":"noin 1090","1145":"1145","about 1115":"noin 1115","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales","of Cynllaith,Swydd y Waun,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1090–":"environ 1090–Décédé","1090–Male":"1090–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1115–1145":"1115–1145","–Male":"Décédé","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","about 1090":"environ 1090","1145":"1145","about 1115":"environ 1115","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Galles","of Cynllaith,Swydd y Waun,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Maredudd ap Robin est né environ 1090, à Denbighshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni, fils de Robin ap Gruffudd. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Gwenhwyfar ferch Madog."},"de":{"about 1090–":"um 1090–Verstorben","1090–Male":"1090–Verstorben","–Female":"Verstorben","1115–1145":"1115–1145","–Male":"Verstorben","1090":"1090","1115":"1115","about 1090":"um 1090","1145":"1145","about 1115":"um 1115","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales","of Cynllaith,Swydd y Waun,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Maredudd ap Robin wurde um 1090 in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom, als Sohn von R